00:00:22.095 --> 00:00:23.470
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
The last time

00:00:23.470 --> 00:00:26.830
we talked a little bit
about Baumol's disease

00:00:26.830 --> 00:00:36.670
and why it affects
products that are not

00:00:36.670 --> 00:00:42.770
seeing technological
change that saves cost.

00:00:42.770 --> 00:00:46.460
And not seeing
import substitution

00:00:46.460 --> 00:00:49.070
that might reduce cost.

00:00:49.070 --> 00:00:53.160
So they tend to grow at faster
than the rate of inflation.

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:58.590
And transit is one
of those activities.

00:00:58.590 --> 00:01:01.740
And what happens is,
the public sector

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:06.180
ends up either taking
the responsibility

00:01:06.180 --> 00:01:09.830
to provide those services,
or subsidizes private parties

00:01:09.830 --> 00:01:11.590
to provide those services.

00:01:11.590 --> 00:01:14.900
Other services
will die or there's

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:16.280
some combination of the two.

00:01:16.280 --> 00:01:19.010
The services get
cut back, and then

00:01:19.010 --> 00:01:23.860
some set of services that
are viewed as too important

00:01:23.860 --> 00:01:28.120
to allow to disappear the
government subsidizes for.

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:35.580
what do you do about it?

00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:36.080
Yes?

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:38.538
AUDIENCE: Just curious, what
are some other things that you

00:01:38.538 --> 00:01:40.110
consider subject
to this problem,

00:01:40.110 --> 00:01:43.590
outside of public
transportation [INAUDIBLE]

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:47.090
like emergency
medical, like fire.

00:01:47.090 --> 00:01:51.410
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Well
certainly fire protection

00:01:51.410 --> 00:02:00.250
services, police, teaching,
education generally,

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:05.580
the health care.

00:02:08.780 --> 00:02:13.760
So what's the cost
problem in health care?

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:19.932
No technological change
going on in health care?

00:02:19.932 --> 00:02:21.590
AUDIENCE: Nothing cost reducing.

00:02:21.590 --> 00:02:23.340
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
Nothing cost reducing.

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:27.880
A sneaky phrase that I put in
was cost reducing technology.

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:30.190
In health care, there's
a lot of technology,

00:02:30.190 --> 00:02:32.770
but it generally
increases costs.

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:38.720
Once there's a better
way to deal with cancer,

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:42.490
we all want it for our
parents, our kids, ourselves.

00:02:42.490 --> 00:02:46.120
So technology and health
care tends to drive costs up.

00:02:48.808 --> 00:02:50.000
For maybe a good thing.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:51.500
It means we're
getting more quality,

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:55.050
but from a cost point
of view, it's cost.

00:02:55.050 --> 00:02:56.300
Yes.

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:57.830
The cynics think
that's a bad thing

00:02:57.830 --> 00:02:59.670
because you cost more money.

00:02:59.670 --> 00:03:03.170
Better you should die quickly
of some disease than hang around

00:03:03.170 --> 00:03:05.770
and need more health care.

00:03:05.770 --> 00:03:10.340
So it gets at some
philosophical questions.

00:03:10.340 --> 00:03:16.320
But it's just from a
practical point of view.

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:19.680
Baumol's disease is
a serious problem

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:22.030
that affects public services.

00:03:22.030 --> 00:03:25.050
And it particularly affects
public transit, which

00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:27.290
is what we're interested here.

00:03:27.290 --> 00:03:32.110
So I don't think we talked
about this last time.

00:03:32.110 --> 00:03:41.180
So what did Baumol say happens
with an activity that's

00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:43.070
afflicted by Baumol's
class disease?

00:03:45.710 --> 00:03:49.160
AUDIENCE: To hire the people
who perform that activity,

00:03:49.160 --> 00:03:50.660
they need to--

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:54.770
their salary needs to be
adjusted to inflation.

00:03:54.770 --> 00:03:57.260
But you're essentially
paying them more and more

00:03:57.260 --> 00:03:59.820
for producing the same amount.

00:03:59.820 --> 00:04:02.010
That's where-- that goes
the musician example.

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:04.730
Because if you want
to hear live music,

00:04:04.730 --> 00:04:07.880
paying musicians 100, 200
years goes the same thing.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:08.954
You have to pay them.

00:04:08.954 --> 00:04:10.620
You had to pay back
then, you pay today.

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:15.242
But today they pay rent
or whatever it is today.

00:04:15.242 --> 00:04:16.700
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
So what's the--

00:04:16.700 --> 00:04:21.990
what's Baumol's
argument about how

00:04:21.990 --> 00:04:29.120
you could continue to have
four string quartets performed

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:29.920
If you choose to?

00:04:32.609 --> 00:04:33.900
You're going to subsidize them.

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:36.080
But what's the economic
rationale that he makes?

00:04:38.790 --> 00:04:41.790
His argument is,
assuming there's

00:04:41.790 --> 00:04:45.645
productivity improvement
in the economy overall,

00:04:45.645 --> 00:04:50.290
the overall gross domestic
product is going up.

00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:54.280
So you actually could
afford to subsidize

00:04:54.280 --> 00:05:01.660
these activities, music, if
you had health care, whatever.

00:05:01.660 --> 00:05:04.240
And you'd still have a
surplus because there's

00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:06.910
been enough growth.

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:13.240
Since it's the-- since it's the
technological change that is

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:25.880
a factor in the
increased wages, then--

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:32.070
and here the theory is that in
the parts of the economy that

00:05:32.070 --> 00:05:38.600
are experiencing introduction
of cost saving technologies,

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:44.260
labor will be able to
get pay increases higher

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:47.650
than the rate of
inflation, because they're

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:52.050
in a position to leverage
that growing productivity.

00:05:52.050 --> 00:05:54.260
Are you with me on that?

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:59.260
So now, the worker
and industry A

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:02.950
that has productivity
improvements

00:06:02.950 --> 00:06:07.500
gets pay increases beyond
the rate of inflation.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:11.480
But if I'm trying
to hire bus drivers,

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:14.240
the bus driver
wants the same pay

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:16.910
because he's living in the
same metropolitan area,

00:06:16.910 --> 00:06:18.680
paying the same rent.

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:21.230
So the bus driver wants to
get the same pay increases

00:06:21.230 --> 00:06:25.670
that the worker in the more
highly productive sector

00:06:25.670 --> 00:06:27.320
is getting.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:32.660
So embedded within the
productivity improvement

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:35.090
is a wage increase.

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:37.310
Now there's a presumption
there that labor

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:40.790
does get a proportionate
share of the productivity

00:06:40.790 --> 00:06:42.620
improvement.

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:44.330
Recently that has
not been happening.

00:06:44.330 --> 00:06:46.820
For a long time that
appeared to be the case when

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:48.590
Baumol was writing.

00:06:48.590 --> 00:06:54.230
So you end up with the
technologically advancing

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:58.160
sector needing to
pay higher wages.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:02.720
The more stagnant
sectors needing

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:05.840
to pay comparable
salaries to attract labor,

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:09.320
because they're working
in the same market.

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:13.160
And therefore, larger and
larger subsidies in those

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:15.142
sectors where productivity
is not improving.

00:07:15.142 --> 00:07:16.600
AUDIENCE: So a
couple of questions.

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:19.899
One, I guess this
assumes full employment.

00:07:19.899 --> 00:07:21.607
If there wasn't full
employment, then you

00:07:21.607 --> 00:07:24.062
would pay bus drivers less
than the more technologically

00:07:24.062 --> 00:07:26.030
advanced employees.

00:07:26.030 --> 00:07:31.010
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Well it
assumes full employment would

00:07:31.010 --> 00:07:33.570
be one way to think about it.

00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:36.750
But if there's not
full employment,

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:39.620
but the workers are organized,
and in transit they're

00:07:39.620 --> 00:07:40.710
very organized.

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:43.480
And they're able to command--

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:46.067
they're able to bargain
for higher wages

00:07:46.067 --> 00:07:47.900
because they can make
the comparison to what

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:51.810
other workers make with
similar educational background.

00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:54.380
And even though there are
unemployed people there,

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:58.640
because the union is able
to control the workplace

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:03.020
to some degree,
even full employment

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:08.270
isn't a necessary
condition for this problem

00:08:08.270 --> 00:08:12.340
to occur and to grow.

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:15.140
AUDIENCE: Being organized is the
necessary condition [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:15.140 --> 00:08:15.410
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes.

00:08:15.410 --> 00:08:17.480
I would argue being
organized is more

00:08:17.480 --> 00:08:19.070
important than full employment.

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:21.760
AUDIENCE: And is that
because, the way I think about

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:25.406
is that because transport is
such an essential service?

00:08:25.406 --> 00:08:26.780
For example, when
I was in London

00:08:26.780 --> 00:08:30.240
the tube shut down like
15 times for strikes.

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:33.337
And the government is really
resistant to increasing wages,

00:08:33.337 --> 00:08:34.420
giving into their demands.

00:08:34.420 --> 00:08:37.159
But eventually they
have to because you're

00:08:37.159 --> 00:08:39.024
losing a billions
dollars in the economy

00:08:39.024 --> 00:08:40.565
or something like
that every time you

00:08:40.565 --> 00:08:41.990
shut down the Tube for a day.

00:08:41.990 --> 00:08:43.460
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes.

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:51.440
So-- Yes, so it's the
practical consequences.

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:54.620
Labor has a lot of leverage.

00:08:54.620 --> 00:08:59.120
And if you think about the
areas we're talking about,

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:03.770
they tend to be areas that
have a high labor content.

00:09:03.770 --> 00:09:05.630
Or they wouldn't
be so vulnerable.

00:09:05.630 --> 00:09:08.420
By the very-- it's
a circular logic.

00:09:08.420 --> 00:09:10.220
They are vulnerable
to Baumol's disease

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:13.430
because they employ
a lot of local labor.

00:09:13.430 --> 00:09:16.490
And the productivity
is not increasing

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:18.890
with technology change.

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:21.430
Therefore, they've
got a growing problem.

00:09:21.430 --> 00:09:24.380
And the problem is compounded
because the workers being

00:09:24.380 --> 00:09:30.290
numerous, and organized, are
able to get those higher pays.

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:32.600
So you're in a bit of a bind.

00:09:32.600 --> 00:09:34.340
So what do you--

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:38.490
you can simply pay more.

00:09:38.490 --> 00:09:44.000
But the other consequence
of having the government

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.850
into the subsidy business
is that other agendas then

00:09:49.850 --> 00:09:51.560
accumulate.

00:09:51.560 --> 00:09:53.960
If Mussolini is in
charge, then you

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:58.040
have to join the Fascist Party
or you're not allowed to sing.

00:09:58.040 --> 00:10:05.010
If Obama is in charge or
some other elected official

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:07.440
that you like better
than Mussolini,

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:11.910
you're still going to get some
political exactions attached

00:10:11.910 --> 00:10:13.350
to subsidy.

00:10:13.350 --> 00:10:15.900
Because get-- the process
of getting subsidy

00:10:15.900 --> 00:10:20.880
through a legislative process
gives people leverage.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:23.640
And there's a
particular problem.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:26.820
Why might the problem
be worse for transit

00:10:26.820 --> 00:10:29.970
than it is, say for education?

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:32.280
Assume for the sake of
argument, education and transit

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:35.700
are similarly dominated
by local labor,

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:40.110
and similarly if afflicted
with Baumol's disease.

00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:43.890
Why might the leverage
issue be different

00:10:43.890 --> 00:10:45.855
in the legislative bodies?

00:10:53.262 --> 00:10:54.720
AUDIENCE: In many
ways the teachers

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:59.410
are like [INAUDIBLE]
employees maybe more

00:10:59.410 --> 00:11:05.550
than the bus driver
[INAUDIBLE] Is it

00:11:05.550 --> 00:11:08.392
because education is
compulsory [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:08.392 --> 00:11:09.500
probably why [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:11.250
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
Well not so much that.

00:11:11.250 --> 00:11:14.130
It's much more Universal.

00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:17.430
Kids in Springfield
need to go to school.

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:21.670
Kids all over Massachusetts
need to go to school.

00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:25.210
North Adams and Pittsfield
don't require the same amount

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:28.649
of transit that the bus
metropolitan area does

00:11:28.649 --> 00:11:30.190
because we're a
congested area, we've

00:11:30.190 --> 00:11:32.260
got a certain kind of economy.

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:34.990
So there's a much higher
proportion, much higher

00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:37.750
dependency on public
transportation

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:39.950
in a place like London,
or a place like Boston,

00:11:39.950 --> 00:11:44.480
than there isn't a
place like North Adams.

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:48.350
So when you're going to
the legislature saying,

00:11:48.350 --> 00:11:51.420
I need money to
subsidize the MBTA,

00:11:51.420 --> 00:11:53.330
the legislator from
a district that

00:11:53.330 --> 00:11:56.000
doesn't get much
service says well,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:57.770
what are you going to give me?

00:11:57.770 --> 00:12:02.420
So why should I vote for this
subsidy so people in Boston

00:12:02.420 --> 00:12:06.972
can ride more convenient
transit at lower cost?

00:12:06.972 --> 00:12:08.180
You've got give me something.

00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:12.770
So the political process
imposes conditions

00:12:12.770 --> 00:12:25.190
on the process of subsidy that
exacts a premium on top of what

00:12:25.190 --> 00:12:27.810
Baumol would have predicted.

00:12:27.810 --> 00:12:32.140
Baumol's analysis
was that it's all

00:12:32.140 --> 00:12:34.060
about competition for labor.

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:36.340
And you're going to be
forced to pay the prevailing

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:40.690
wage in that metropolitan area
in order to attract labor,

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:43.300
because there are competing
opportunities for workers

00:12:43.300 --> 00:12:43.870
to work.

00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:45.970
Let's assume it's
full employment,

00:12:45.970 --> 00:12:48.040
possibly it's because
of the leverage

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:52.370
in the workplace of the union.

00:12:52.370 --> 00:12:54.850
But you're going to have to
pay that metropolitan area

00:12:54.850 --> 00:12:55.980
competitive wage.

00:12:55.980 --> 00:12:59.920
But what Baumol
isn't calculating

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:02.410
is that the very process
of getting subsidy out

00:13:02.410 --> 00:13:07.030
of the political process
imposes these extra costs.

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:11.320
So this is all me
rambling theory.

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:12.840
So a couple of years--

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:14.340
AUDIENCE: Pure-hearted
politicians.

00:13:14.340 --> 00:13:15.340
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes.

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:17.200
Even with good politicians
that are really

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.989
trying to do the right thing,
they want to support transit.

00:13:19.989 --> 00:13:22.530
They have to convince voters in
other parts of the state that

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:25.280
don't have much transit
to put money into it.

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:28.300
They've got to do
something different.

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:34.120
I mean, in Massachusetts for a
long time what Western Mass was

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:36.970
getting out of the
state government

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:39.100
was the University of
Massachusetts payroll.

00:13:39.100 --> 00:13:42.760
Because UMass was located
out Amherst, there were jobs.

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:45.720
It was a very important
part of the economy

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:47.920
that's not very robust.

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:51.970
There were heavy subsidies
to higher public education.

00:13:51.970 --> 00:13:54.700
Eastern Mass, in
an earlier period,

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:57.790
was much more dominated
by private universities.

00:13:57.790 --> 00:13:59.170
Now there's a UMass Boston.

00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:00.640
But in an early
period was really

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:02.470
all concentrated out there.

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:06.970
So the rough trade was, OK
you got the T, I got UMass.

00:14:06.970 --> 00:14:13.990
But there is some price attached
by the political process

00:14:13.990 --> 00:14:15.370
to providing subsidy.

00:14:15.370 --> 00:14:21.430
Because in the more unevenly
spread the service is,

00:14:21.430 --> 00:14:23.680
the higher that
price is going to be.

00:14:23.680 --> 00:14:28.290
That's me making up theory
and asking you to believe it.

00:14:28.290 --> 00:14:30.970
So a couple of
years ago, a couple

00:14:30.970 --> 00:14:33.910
of times in the
past few decades,

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:39.220
I've been lucky enough to have
a lot of very smart students

00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:41.440
doing their masters degrees.

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:45.100
So I've inflicted Baumol's
disease on a couple of them.

00:14:45.100 --> 00:14:51.190
So [INAUDIBLE],, I'm going to
mangle his name, [INAUDIBLE]..

00:14:51.190 --> 00:14:55.430
Have you guys read
his work at all?

00:14:55.430 --> 00:14:58.380
He is a brilliant
guy from Jordan.

00:14:58.380 --> 00:14:59.460
Very interesting fellow.

00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:03.690
He did a really nice
piece on Baumol's disease,

00:15:03.690 --> 00:15:05.970
and somewhat theoretical piece.

00:15:05.970 --> 00:15:09.060
And showed, yes, it looks
like transit really has it.

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:10.660
Then a couple of
years ago, there

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:13.900
was another student
named Javier.

00:15:13.900 --> 00:15:15.660
I think some of you knew Javier.

00:15:15.660 --> 00:15:19.680
So he got-- he did
an analysis where

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:24.420
he looked at a large dataset.

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:28.900
I think he looked at something
like 700 transit agencies.

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:32.690
And he was just looking at bus
services in the United States.

00:15:32.690 --> 00:15:38.760
And he found that the MBTA has
Baumol's disease, number one.

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:42.190
Number two, every bus
provider in the United States

00:15:42.190 --> 00:15:43.360
has Baumol's disease.

00:15:43.360 --> 00:15:46.180
It's not unique to the T.
We think the T is worse,

00:15:46.180 --> 00:15:47.285
it's actually not.

00:15:47.285 --> 00:15:49.390
It's a problem everywhere.

00:15:49.390 --> 00:15:57.260
Number three, there is
a premium above what

00:15:57.260 --> 00:15:58.910
Baumol would have predicted.

00:15:58.910 --> 00:16:03.290
Baumol would have predicted
this metropolitan area

00:16:03.290 --> 00:16:05.000
comparable wage.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.630
But in fact transit wages
are raising perversely, not

00:16:09.630 --> 00:16:11.760
only higher than
inflation, but higher

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:14.160
than the salaries of
comparably skilled workers

00:16:14.160 --> 00:16:17.100
in the same metropolitan area.

00:16:17.100 --> 00:16:23.210
And the only explanation
I could figure out

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:26.300
is the leverage of the
legislative process.

00:16:26.300 --> 00:16:28.820
We've got two kinds of leverage,
the leverage of the workers

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:31.260
in the union
bargaining position.

00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:34.850
But then you got the
leverage of other legislators

00:16:34.850 --> 00:16:40.310
who insist on some
additional price to be paid.

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:47.470
But you've got labor
also commanding power

00:16:47.470 --> 00:16:49.940
in the legislative process.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:53.950
So now, if I'm
running the T and I

00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:57.700
need to go to the
legislature to get money,

00:16:57.700 --> 00:17:01.720
the theory is that I'm
the boss and there's

00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:05.740
this sort of structure and
these workers work for me.

00:17:05.740 --> 00:17:07.420
The fact is, the
workers have way

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:11.290
more power than I do in
talking to the legislature,

00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:14.609
because the union
has a lot of voters.

00:17:14.609 --> 00:17:17.670
And they're disciplined, and
they can deliver that vote.

00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:19.420
And they can deliver
workers, and they can

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:21.890
deliver campaign contribution.

00:17:21.890 --> 00:17:23.770
And I'm trying to
peddle public policy,

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:26.650
and transit is good for
you, and you should do this.

00:17:26.650 --> 00:17:30.310
So I really need
labor as an ally

00:17:30.310 --> 00:17:34.360
in getting the support of the
legislature for the subsidy.

00:17:34.360 --> 00:17:38.920
And, perversely, labor figures
that out and demands even more.

00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:43.240
So sounds weird,
but Javier's data

00:17:43.240 --> 00:17:44.920
shows this is
absolutely the case.

00:17:44.920 --> 00:17:47.110
That there is a premium
above and beyond

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:50.230
what Baumol would
have predicted.

00:17:50.230 --> 00:17:51.730
And it's all over
the United States.

00:17:51.730 --> 00:17:54.010
Then he took another look.

00:17:54.010 --> 00:17:59.410
And we made up a couple of
tests of what might an indicator

00:17:59.410 --> 00:18:04.210
be of the relative
political strength of labor

00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:08.270
in a state or a
local jurisdiction.

00:18:08.270 --> 00:18:14.570
So do any of you know what
the right to work laws are?

00:18:14.570 --> 00:18:18.745
So what's a right to work law?

00:18:18.745 --> 00:18:21.320
AUDIENCE: It's a
law that [INAUDIBLE]

