00:30:44.650 --> 00:30:46.460
But it's certainly an offset.

00:30:46.460 --> 00:30:51.681
And that's-- none of you
guys are going to rat me out,

00:30:51.681 --> 00:30:52.180
are you?

00:30:52.180 --> 00:30:55.250
This thing is being
taped isn't it?

00:30:55.250 --> 00:30:57.533
AUDIENCE: Maybe an eighth of us.

00:30:57.533 --> 00:30:58.465
[INAUDIBLE]

00:30:58.465 --> 00:31:00.840
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Well,
we've got our visitors from TFL

00:31:00.840 --> 00:31:01.700
coming tomorrow.

00:31:01.700 --> 00:31:02.949
And they they're great people.

00:31:02.949 --> 00:31:05.010
And it's a very
competent organization.

00:31:05.010 --> 00:31:06.510
And they're very
proud of themselves

00:31:06.510 --> 00:31:07.860
for running a good service.

00:31:07.860 --> 00:31:12.600
And they, in fact,
for a long time

00:31:12.600 --> 00:31:15.420
were able to persuade
two different mayors.

00:31:15.420 --> 00:31:19.180
One, the labor mayor
red Ken Livingstone

00:31:19.180 --> 00:31:23.520
the Trotskyite, and then
the right wing conservative

00:31:23.520 --> 00:31:26.910
mayor Boris.

00:31:26.910 --> 00:31:31.080
And they were able to convince
the Trotskyite, as well

00:31:31.080 --> 00:31:35.100
as the conservative
that it was OK to try

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:41.760
to increase transit fares by
the rate of inflation plus 1%.

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:45.750
That's a pretty steep,
especially for a labor

00:31:45.750 --> 00:31:47.250
kind of mayor.

00:31:47.250 --> 00:31:49.350
The current mayor
is a socialist,

00:31:49.350 --> 00:31:52.110
and he's not into
seeing that continue.

00:31:52.110 --> 00:31:53.610
And I don't blame him.

00:31:53.610 --> 00:31:58.941
But TFL was really happy
that they had this strategy.

00:31:58.941 --> 00:32:00.690
And of course they
argued that well, we're

00:32:00.690 --> 00:32:01.930
providing better service.

00:32:01.930 --> 00:32:03.804
So people should pay
for that better service.

00:32:03.804 --> 00:32:07.020
And to some degree that's true.

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:11.030
And their numbers were
looking very good.

00:32:11.030 --> 00:32:15.770
But it turned out that
the population of London

00:32:15.770 --> 00:32:19.190
had grown in the previous five
years, more than anyone knew.

00:32:19.190 --> 00:32:24.350
So there was a secret assist
to the numbers coming out

00:32:24.350 --> 00:32:26.930
of the fact that the
population had just grown,

00:32:26.930 --> 00:32:28.550
along with a growing economy.

00:32:28.550 --> 00:32:31.430
And not to take anything away
from a very competent bunch

00:32:31.430 --> 00:32:34.610
of people running TFL, they
were in the right place

00:32:34.610 --> 00:32:35.500
at the right time.

00:32:35.500 --> 00:32:39.820
You bunt on third base and
think you hit a triple.

00:32:39.820 --> 00:32:41.720
Here we are.

00:32:41.720 --> 00:32:44.510
You're in London with
this terrific system,

00:32:44.510 --> 00:32:47.060
and the economy is growing,
and it's kind of going up.

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:50.050
Now it's a little unfair
because they are very competent,

00:32:50.050 --> 00:32:52.650
and they're doing a good job,
and they work hard at it.

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:55.531
But a lot of it is just luck
of being in the right place

00:32:55.531 --> 00:32:56.280
at the right time.

00:32:56.280 --> 00:33:02.180
So there's an external
extra benefit to transit

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:06.530
that can help offset Baumol's
disease in those cities that

00:33:06.530 --> 00:33:07.122
are growing.

00:33:07.122 --> 00:33:09.080
So what do you do in a
city that's not growing?

00:33:09.080 --> 00:33:10.400
What do you do in North Adams?

00:33:10.400 --> 00:33:13.670
What do you do when General
Electric pulls out a Pittsfield

00:33:13.670 --> 00:33:16.060
yanking 5,000 jobs with them?

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:18.920
You know you don't have that
luck in those situations.

00:33:18.920 --> 00:33:24.080
So it's nice to be
lucky, but you can't bank

00:33:24.080 --> 00:33:25.490
on that in a systematic way.

00:33:25.490 --> 00:33:28.402
And you need to be able to
sort of look at the situation

00:33:28.402 --> 00:33:29.360
and think that through.

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:39.060
So another place you
might get funding support,

00:33:39.060 --> 00:33:42.410
and this is very hard to do,
and they successfully did this

00:33:42.410 --> 00:33:44.042
to some degree in London.

00:33:44.042 --> 00:33:48.380
Is to try to secure
funding support, at least

00:33:48.380 --> 00:33:53.570
political support, from
those growth constituencies.

00:33:53.570 --> 00:34:00.850
So the easy thing to do, not
easy, all of this is tough.

00:34:00.850 --> 00:34:04.750
But the relatively
feasible thing to do

00:34:04.750 --> 00:34:07.570
is to identify the
beneficiaries of what

00:34:07.570 --> 00:34:10.510
you're doing, above
and beyond those people

00:34:10.510 --> 00:34:12.929
riding on the system.

00:34:12.929 --> 00:34:15.076
So you look at what's going on.

00:34:15.076 --> 00:34:17.659
And you say, hey, there's a much
real estate developers making

00:34:17.659 --> 00:34:18.980
a lot of money.

00:34:18.980 --> 00:34:23.420
And they couldn't develop those
densities except for transit.

00:34:23.420 --> 00:34:29.630
So let me go to them and try to
get them to politically support

00:34:29.630 --> 00:34:32.810
taxes that someone else
will pay so that there

00:34:32.810 --> 00:34:34.699
can be better transit.

00:34:34.699 --> 00:34:37.639
That's the easier lift, right?

00:34:37.639 --> 00:34:40.070
Let's increase the sales tax.

00:34:40.070 --> 00:34:42.889
Real estate developers don't
pay particularly more sales tax

00:34:42.889 --> 00:34:45.559
than other people do.

00:34:45.559 --> 00:34:47.850
Everybody tries to do things
with other people's money.

00:34:47.850 --> 00:34:50.540
So I can make a
campaign contribution,

00:34:50.540 --> 00:34:53.300
raise the sales tax, have
a better transit system,

00:34:53.300 --> 00:34:55.530
my real estate value
goes up, I make money.

00:34:55.530 --> 00:34:58.010
That's one proposition.

00:34:58.010 --> 00:34:59.480
That doesn't happen
automatically.

00:34:59.480 --> 00:35:02.710
It's hard to do,
but it's doable.

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:09.340
A more significant,
more significant

00:35:09.340 --> 00:35:14.850
achievement was what transport
for London pulled off

00:35:14.850 --> 00:35:17.230
on the funding of Crossrail.

00:35:17.230 --> 00:35:20.770
Because they went to the
financial services community

00:35:20.770 --> 00:35:25.720
that really wanted
Crossrail because they see--

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:28.030
they've learned a little
bit from the experience

00:35:28.030 --> 00:35:30.790
that when Docklands
light rail got built,

00:35:30.790 --> 00:35:34.090
all of a sudden these Docklands
that were kind of abandoned

00:35:34.090 --> 00:35:39.490
start to be successful, and too
successful, and hard to get to.

00:35:39.490 --> 00:35:44.110
And then they do the Jubilee
line, and another growth spurt,

00:35:44.110 --> 00:35:45.070
and wow.

00:35:45.070 --> 00:35:47.142
The economy's
growing, this is good.

00:35:47.142 --> 00:35:48.100
Now let's do Crossrail.

00:35:48.100 --> 00:35:50.230
We're going to really
get a massive amount

00:35:50.230 --> 00:35:54.730
of additional crosstown
capacity, very

00:35:54.730 --> 00:35:56.020
large investment.

00:35:56.020 --> 00:35:57.340
It's two big digs.

00:35:57.340 --> 00:36:00.960
It's like we use the Big Dig
as a unit of measurement,

00:36:00.960 --> 00:36:04.554
that's about $25 billion, I
think it's $25 billion pounds.

00:36:04.554 --> 00:36:05.470
Does that sound right?

00:36:05.470 --> 00:36:07.662
AUDIENCE: I just
know it's a lot.

00:36:07.662 --> 00:36:09.370
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
It's a big, big deal.

00:36:13.454 --> 00:36:15.120
So how are you going
to fund that thing?

00:36:15.120 --> 00:36:16.590
Well, let's go to the
national governments

00:36:16.590 --> 00:36:17.610
and say hey, give us some money.

00:36:17.610 --> 00:36:18.540
This is virtuous.

00:36:18.540 --> 00:36:19.950
Here's our benefit
cost analysis.

00:36:19.950 --> 00:36:21.660
Look how wonderful it is.

00:36:21.660 --> 00:36:25.440
And the national government
say, get out of here.

00:36:25.440 --> 00:36:28.820
We've got a political problem,
too much going to London.

00:36:28.820 --> 00:36:32.640
Lots of parts of the UK
that aren't so successful.

00:36:32.640 --> 00:36:35.690
They're not very sympathetic,
so forget about it.

00:36:38.870 --> 00:36:40.970
What they end up at
the end of the story

00:36:40.970 --> 00:36:43.700
without going through
the various attempts,

00:36:43.700 --> 00:36:46.130
is they convinced--

00:36:46.130 --> 00:36:49.260
they put together a package
that has three components.

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:55.100
One, they pledged to defray a
third of the costs of Crossrail

00:36:55.100 --> 00:36:59.540
by continually increasing
transit revenues.

00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:01.820
That can be through
more riders, or it

00:37:01.820 --> 00:37:03.830
can be the same riders
at higher fares,

00:37:03.830 --> 00:37:05.700
or a combination of the two.

00:37:05.700 --> 00:37:07.422
But a third of the
capital cost is

00:37:07.422 --> 00:37:09.380
going to come out of the
riders because they're

00:37:09.380 --> 00:37:12.530
going to be beneficiaries
of less crowded conditions,

00:37:12.530 --> 00:37:15.500
and more convenient service.

00:37:15.500 --> 00:37:19.400
A third of it will get
from the government.

00:37:19.400 --> 00:37:22.100
And a third of it
we're going to put

00:37:22.100 --> 00:37:28.400
a surcharge on the real
estate tax of large companies

00:37:28.400 --> 00:37:32.330
in London, on the
commercial real estate.

00:37:32.330 --> 00:37:34.970
Not the little corner
store, but anything

00:37:34.970 --> 00:37:38.090
bigger than some minimum.

00:37:38.090 --> 00:37:39.470
Now that's a hard ask.

00:37:39.470 --> 00:37:42.260
Because now you're saying
to someone, admit it,

00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:44.060
you're a beneficiary,
and you should

00:37:44.060 --> 00:37:47.570
be willing to actually put some
of your money on the table.

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:49.640
And they're never going
to agree with you because

00:37:49.640 --> 00:37:52.070
of the ethical argument.

00:37:52.070 --> 00:37:54.080
It's the practical
argument look,

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:56.510
we can ask for 100 percent
national money all we want,

00:37:56.510 --> 00:37:57.740
they're never going to do it.

00:37:57.740 --> 00:37:59.690
We've got to have
something different.

00:37:59.690 --> 00:38:02.900
So they put together this a
third, a third, a third package

00:38:02.900 --> 00:38:04.610
and they succeeded.

00:38:04.610 --> 00:38:09.150
Now, the national government
is the most fraudulent

00:38:09.150 --> 00:38:10.980
of the three parties.

00:38:10.980 --> 00:38:14.250
Because if you think
of the, and this

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:16.740
was true with the
alleged labor government

00:38:16.740 --> 00:38:20.640
then even more true
with the conservatives.

00:38:20.640 --> 00:38:26.590
What's the marginal rate of
income taxation in the UK right

00:38:26.590 --> 00:38:27.090
now?

00:38:27.090 --> 00:38:29.425
AUDIENCE: Well it depends
on what bracket you're in,

00:38:29.425 --> 00:38:32.130
but the highest bracket is
45% above 150,000 pounds.

00:38:32.130 --> 00:38:33.880
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
OK, and what if you're

00:38:33.880 --> 00:38:37.092
say 80,000, 50,000 pounds?

00:38:37.092 --> 00:38:39.810
AUDIENCE: You pay like a
marginal rate of like 30%.

00:38:39.810 --> 00:38:42.520
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: OK 30%.

00:38:42.520 --> 00:38:46.310
So [INTERPOSING VOICES]
Yeah so 30%.

00:38:46.310 --> 00:38:49.060
So we're going to
build Crossrail.

00:38:49.060 --> 00:38:53.280
This is an unusual burst
of construction activity.

00:38:53.280 --> 00:38:56.892
We're going to import a bunch of
Polish workers to do the work.

00:38:56.892 --> 00:38:59.100
They're going to leave their
wives and kids back home

00:38:59.100 --> 00:39:02.280
in Poland, getting
educated back there.

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:05.250
They're going to live
on marginal conditions

00:39:05.250 --> 00:39:09.060
where they are, and the
national governments taking 30%

00:39:09.060 --> 00:39:10.440
off the top of what they make.

00:39:10.440 --> 00:39:12.660
Maybe more than 30%.

00:39:12.660 --> 00:39:15.300
So this one third that
the national government

00:39:15.300 --> 00:39:17.700
contributed, they're
getting it all back

00:39:17.700 --> 00:39:24.390
from what they're taking out
of that blip in employment

00:39:24.390 --> 00:39:25.677
that the project is causing.

00:39:25.677 --> 00:39:27.510
So they're the most
fraudulent of the three.

00:39:27.510 --> 00:39:30.030
They're not really
contributing, but boy they

00:39:30.030 --> 00:39:35.820
made them crawl through a
sewer pipe to get the money.

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:43.420
But the point is,
you need to identify

00:39:43.420 --> 00:39:46.300
who the beneficiaries are.

00:39:46.300 --> 00:39:50.130
And, at the very least, you
need to enlist their support

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:52.920
to get someone
else to pay taxes.

00:39:52.920 --> 00:39:54.750
And you may not
get away with that.

00:39:54.750 --> 00:39:57.960
So you may have to do something
to make the constituency

00:39:57.960 --> 00:40:01.020
that benefits put some of
their own money on the table.

00:40:01.020 --> 00:40:02.880
And the analog on
that in Boston would

00:40:02.880 --> 00:40:06.240
be, it's very nice to get
federal and state money

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:08.911
to upgrade transit services.

00:40:08.911 --> 00:40:10.410
But that's state
money is coming out

00:40:10.410 --> 00:40:14.850
of parts of the state that
are much less affluent.

00:40:14.850 --> 00:40:19.800
So why shouldn't Boston and
Cambridge and Somerville

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:23.340
put some money into
both the operation

00:40:23.340 --> 00:40:25.800
and maintenance of the service.

00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:29.250
Seems to me, there's an ethical
argument that they ought to.

00:40:29.250 --> 00:40:32.342
And there's a stronger political
argument that they better,

00:40:32.342 --> 00:40:34.050
because the rest of
the state's not going

00:40:34.050 --> 00:40:36.380
to pay for Boston anymore.

00:40:36.380 --> 00:40:40.080
Boston's doing too well
economically to expect sympathy

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:42.570
from the rest of
the state on paying

00:40:42.570 --> 00:40:44.190
for the investment
in the services

00:40:44.190 --> 00:40:46.330
that the Boston
economy requires.

00:40:46.330 --> 00:40:48.690
So the point is,
if you're trying

00:40:48.690 --> 00:40:53.270
to deal with the Baumol problem,
and you are, you can be lucky

00:40:53.270 --> 00:40:54.260
and that's nice.

00:40:54.260 --> 00:40:55.640
And you should at
least recognize

00:40:55.640 --> 00:40:56.750
that you're being lucky.

00:40:56.750 --> 00:41:00.740
But then you also have to say
who are the beneficiaries?

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:03.890
If I make up this fancy
externality argument

00:41:03.890 --> 00:41:06.950
that it's good for society
for there to be more transit,

00:41:06.950 --> 00:41:08.990
there must be some real
human beings in back

00:41:08.990 --> 00:41:10.220
of that external benefit.

00:41:10.220 --> 00:41:12.030
I better figure
out who they are.

00:41:12.030 --> 00:41:14.930
And at the very least, get
them to support me politically,

00:41:14.930 --> 00:41:17.750
and preferably even willing
to put some of their own money

00:41:17.750 --> 00:41:18.450
on the table.

00:41:18.450 --> 00:41:20.720
So it's kind of a thought
process to go through.

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:32.720
Another strategy that is
often, maybe to greater degree

00:41:32.720 --> 00:41:38.590
described as a panacea, and that
is well, let's contract out.

00:41:38.590 --> 00:41:43.690
These unions are,
not to be pejorative,

00:41:43.690 --> 00:41:45.340
they're just too
good at what they do.

00:41:45.340 --> 00:41:47.310
It's not that they
are nasty people.

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:49.694
That they've got leverage,
and they're using it.

00:41:49.694 --> 00:41:50.860
They think that's their job.

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:55.780
They're getting more wages and
benefits for their employees.

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:57.490
So why would you be surprised.

00:41:57.490 --> 00:42:00.310
But you're having
a real problem.

00:42:00.310 --> 00:42:09.020
So if you contract out,
maybe you won't pay as much

00:42:09.020 --> 00:42:14.190
of a Baumol premium.

00:42:14.190 --> 00:42:19.620
Now, deconstruct
what I just said.

00:42:19.620 --> 00:42:21.610
Do you buy that?

00:42:21.610 --> 00:42:25.160
What if we contracted out
all the bus service for the T

00:42:25.160 --> 00:42:28.440
to third party?

00:42:28.440 --> 00:42:32.222
So Paul Revere could
run everything.

00:42:32.222 --> 00:42:37.442
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] So you'd
have to bribe them somehow.

00:42:37.442 --> 00:42:39.900
You can't have-- you couldn't
have one private service when

00:42:39.900 --> 00:42:41.910
the whole thing, because
they'd just unionized

00:42:41.910 --> 00:42:43.630
to the private service.

00:42:43.630 --> 00:42:46.230
Unless there was some
kind of right to work law

00:42:46.230 --> 00:42:48.500
that was passed [INAUDIBLE]
in Massachusetts.

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:53.680
So you'd have to like contract
it out to 30 agencies.

00:42:53.680 --> 00:42:57.790
And they would also all have
to have a different union

00:42:57.790 --> 00:42:59.280
[INAUDIBLE] random.

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:02.770
Rather than all joining some
one Transit Workers Union.

00:43:02.770 --> 00:43:05.870
I don't think there's any, now
thinking it out, any way you

00:43:05.870 --> 00:43:09.230
could force them to do that.

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:13.250
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
So you're saying

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:18.042
if you can't do that it's
of no value to contract out?

00:43:18.042 --> 00:43:19.750
AUDIENCE: I don't
think it's of no value,

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:21.710
but I think it's
of marginal value.

00:43:24.650 --> 00:43:27.160
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
Anybody want to argue?

00:43:27.160 --> 00:43:28.990
You got a little more
than that out of it?

00:43:33.459 --> 00:43:35.000
AUDIENCE: I think
I know we're going.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:38.690
But still hopefully
this is [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:38.690 --> 00:43:42.120
that you can sort of by
contracting some of it out,

00:43:42.120 --> 00:43:44.385
you can have a check on
the power of the unions.

00:43:44.385 --> 00:43:45.760
And sort of what
you're saying is

00:43:45.760 --> 00:43:48.630
that you can have sort
of two systems that

00:43:48.630 --> 00:43:54.010
keep each other in line
with one system [INAUDIBLE]..

00:43:54.010 --> 00:43:56.940
I guess the problem, like
the problem with unions

00:43:56.940 --> 00:43:59.760
is they're often not
necessarily based on the company

00:43:59.760 --> 00:44:00.860
you work for.

00:44:00.860 --> 00:44:02.830
They're often based
on a type of trade.

00:44:02.830 --> 00:44:05.910
So you could end up
having two companies that

00:44:05.910 --> 00:44:08.540
run bus services,
but actually they all

00:44:08.540 --> 00:44:10.100
destroy the bus [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:12.016
And it's quite possible
that in the short-term

00:44:12.016 --> 00:44:14.610
you might have more competition
than longer-term [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:17.920
basically [INAUDIBLE]

