00:46:43.350 --> 00:46:48.510
But that the cost performance
is consistently better

00:46:48.510 --> 00:46:52.120
in those places that do a
combination of contracting out

00:46:52.120 --> 00:46:53.520
and in-house.

00:46:53.520 --> 00:46:56.057
And that's probably partly
because once the contractors

00:46:56.057 --> 00:46:58.390
figure out you don't know how
to do it yourself anymore.

00:46:58.390 --> 00:46:59.820
They get you over a barrel.

00:46:59.820 --> 00:47:02.220
And they take advantage
of the leverage.

00:47:02.220 --> 00:47:05.970
And it's partly because
you can't manage something

00:47:05.970 --> 00:47:07.740
if you don't know how
to do it yourself.

00:47:07.740 --> 00:47:10.980
So when you're contracting
out, the transit manager

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:13.510
has to know how to
manage that contract.

00:47:13.510 --> 00:47:17.640
And if you're not doing anything
in-house that's a weakness.

00:47:17.640 --> 00:47:23.250
So that indicates that the mixed
strategy seems better than all

00:47:23.250 --> 00:47:25.220
of one or all of the other.

00:47:25.220 --> 00:47:26.850
But if you had to
choose, you might

00:47:26.850 --> 00:47:29.820
choose for the
contracted model based

00:47:29.820 --> 00:47:31.230
on the way the numbers look.

00:47:31.230 --> 00:47:36.390
But the half and half or
the part that, some of each,

00:47:36.390 --> 00:47:39.744
seems to be a better strategy.

00:47:39.744 --> 00:47:45.230
AUDIENCE: Is it also the case
that maybe some services are

00:47:45.230 --> 00:47:48.045
going to be run more
