00:47:48.045 --> 00:47:52.715
whereas some services can be
run more efficiently in-house?

00:47:52.715 --> 00:47:54.302
Plus it makes sense
to contract out

00:47:54.302 --> 00:47:58.810
when those services that can be
done more efficiently that way.

00:48:02.690 --> 00:48:05.030
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: It's
possible, but I don't think so.

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:09.440
I mean a bad, and
unscrupulous manager,

00:48:09.440 --> 00:48:13.070
or a set of
unscrupulous employees

00:48:13.070 --> 00:48:16.400
could, for example,
look at a bus

00:48:16.400 --> 00:48:22.190
route that is not very full.

00:48:22.190 --> 00:48:25.430
But there's a policy
headway that says well

00:48:25.430 --> 00:48:28.370
even if the bus isn't
full we should not

00:48:28.370 --> 00:48:33.350
provide less than a bus every
15 minutes in this corridor.

00:48:33.350 --> 00:48:39.240
An unscrupulous manager or an
unscrupulous union might say,

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:43.470
all these people will fit in a
bus every 30 minutes, screw it.

00:48:43.470 --> 00:48:45.590
We're just going to
run half the service.

00:48:45.590 --> 00:48:47.910
And if they don't get caught
they'll pocket the money

00:48:47.910 --> 00:48:49.870
if it's a contractor.

00:48:49.870 --> 00:48:53.490
And if it's the workers,
they'll just play cards and not

00:48:53.490 --> 00:48:54.680
run half the routes.

00:48:54.680 --> 00:49:06.094
In Puerto Rico when we were
doing work there the story was,

00:49:06.094 --> 00:49:07.510
I don't know if
you have verified.

00:49:07.510 --> 00:49:11.500
Discovery was one for
me, one for the company.

00:49:11.500 --> 00:49:14.470
The schedule says there's
a bus every 15 minutes,

00:49:14.470 --> 00:49:15.860
we run one every 30 minutes.

00:49:15.860 --> 00:49:18.940
That's good enough, and we
play dominoes in between.

00:49:18.940 --> 00:49:20.638
Have you heard the story?

00:49:20.638 --> 00:49:25.618
AUDIENCE: Well when I consulted
for them and with [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:25.618 --> 00:49:30.750
that was the case [INAUDIBLE]
The reality is that they didn't

00:49:30.750 --> 00:49:35.210
have the buses to operate,
no buses in good condition.

00:49:35.210 --> 00:49:38.070
So they only had half the fleet.

00:49:38.070 --> 00:49:43.624
So we couldn't pull
out [INAUDIBLE] Sot

00:49:43.624 --> 00:49:45.556
it ended up being what you said.

00:49:45.556 --> 00:49:46.094
[INAUDIBLE]

00:49:46.094 --> 00:49:48.010
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: So
anyway what I'm saying,

00:49:48.010 --> 00:49:50.220
though, is that
you could view it

00:49:50.220 --> 00:49:55.380
as a kind of corrupt
practice by a contractor.

00:49:55.380 --> 00:49:58.320
Or you could view it as an
unethical practice by workers.

00:49:58.320 --> 00:50:06.270
But there's leverage in a market
where policy wants a better

00:50:06.270 --> 00:50:11.430
level of service than
the service requires

00:50:11.430 --> 00:50:12.390
in market terms.

00:50:12.390 --> 00:50:14.640
There aren't enough
people paying fares.

00:50:14.640 --> 00:50:16.470
Because you lose
some riders when you

00:50:16.470 --> 00:50:19.410
mistreat your riders that way.

00:50:19.410 --> 00:50:21.780
But if your fares
are low, and you're

00:50:21.780 --> 00:50:27.780
mostly dependent on
subsidy, then your customer,

00:50:27.780 --> 00:50:30.030
if you will, whether
you are employees

00:50:30.030 --> 00:50:32.370
or whether you're a
company, your customer

00:50:32.370 --> 00:50:36.060
is the agency paying
you with subsidy.

00:50:36.060 --> 00:50:38.430
Your customer is
not the rider who's

00:50:38.430 --> 00:50:40.410
paying a fare to get a service.

00:50:40.410 --> 00:50:48.180
So you've changed the dynamic of
who your institution is trying

00:50:48.180 --> 00:50:50.130
to please in its behavior.

00:50:50.130 --> 00:50:54.840
And workers aren't particularly
better than companies

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:57.800
in exploiting
situations like that.

00:50:57.800 --> 00:50:59.400
It happens both ways.

00:50:59.400 --> 00:51:07.710
So the theory is that you
won't get the benefits

00:51:07.710 --> 00:51:12.520
unless there is competition
among different companies.

00:51:12.520 --> 00:51:14.880
If you go to
private contracting.

00:51:14.880 --> 00:51:17.130
Even if you only do
partial contracting.

00:51:17.130 --> 00:51:18.682
You look at the
data and say well,

00:51:18.682 --> 00:51:20.140
I'm not going to
make that mistake.

00:51:20.140 --> 00:51:21.135
I'm going to do some.

00:51:21.135 --> 00:51:25.170
You still would like to
have multiple companies.

00:51:25.170 --> 00:51:29.580
Well, in some areas there
aren't multiple companies.

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:32.580
You can't just will
them into existence.

00:51:32.580 --> 00:51:38.730
And if your objective
in the competition

00:51:38.730 --> 00:51:42.930
is to minimize the amount
you're paying in subsidy,

00:51:42.930 --> 00:51:46.170
you may make this such
a marginal business

00:51:46.170 --> 00:51:49.950
that it's quite unattractive
for people to come into it.

00:51:49.950 --> 00:51:56.820
So if you've got a strategy to
control Baumol's disease based

00:51:56.820 --> 00:52:02.580
on contracting out, you can't
be excessively cost conscious

00:52:02.580 --> 00:52:04.650
or you will destroy
the incentive

00:52:04.650 --> 00:52:07.000
for people to be part of it.

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.790
So you've got to think
about why you're doing it.

00:52:09.790 --> 00:52:13.410
Now, if you're
doing it to improve

00:52:13.410 --> 00:52:18.870
the quality of the service,
and to provide more service,

00:52:18.870 --> 00:52:28.090
then you may be able to have a
growing business opportunity.

00:52:28.090 --> 00:52:32.100
So that more companies will
want to come into the area

00:52:32.100 --> 00:52:34.540
because it looks like a
good place to do business.

00:52:34.540 --> 00:52:37.430
But if it's a kind of
stable, 10 years from now

00:52:37.430 --> 00:52:40.100
is the same number
of riders is today,

00:52:40.100 --> 00:52:41.900
it's a pretty dead end business.

00:52:41.900 --> 00:52:46.130
So you're not going to really
get top managers trying

00:52:46.130 --> 00:52:50.480
to provide better
service for less money,

00:52:50.480 --> 00:52:53.480
either in the public sector
or when you contract out.

00:52:53.480 --> 00:52:55.610
But there's a more
fundamental theoretical thing.

00:52:55.610 --> 00:52:58.890
And I'm going on too
long about Baumol.

00:52:58.890 --> 00:53:02.480
But what's the maximum
you would expect

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:08.490
to get out of a strategy of
contracting out and getting

00:53:08.490 --> 00:53:10.560
competition?

00:53:10.560 --> 00:53:12.870
Would you totally offset
the Baumol's disease?

00:53:15.525 --> 00:53:17.440
AUDIENCE: Just delay.

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:20.946
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: So why
are you saying no, Leo?

00:53:20.946 --> 00:53:29.545
AUDIENCE: Because [INAUDIBLE]
People [INAUDIBLE]

00:53:29.545 --> 00:53:33.330
That's the way I feel
[INAUDIBLE] actually brings

00:53:33.330 --> 00:53:36.290
a lot of the fighting
between the two parties.

00:53:36.290 --> 00:53:41.394
You have to realize that
they don't [INAUDIBLE]..

00:53:41.394 --> 00:53:43.560
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: There's
some of that but there's

00:53:43.560 --> 00:53:45.390
a more fundamental issue.

00:53:45.390 --> 00:53:48.690
The theory that
Baumol put forward

00:53:48.690 --> 00:53:50.430
is that in order
to attract labor

00:53:50.430 --> 00:53:52.890
you're going to have
to pay the prevailing

00:53:52.890 --> 00:53:54.660
wage in the metropolitan area.

00:53:54.660 --> 00:53:57.620
And therefore, you
are stuck with costs

00:53:57.620 --> 00:54:00.330
to grow faster than
the rate of inflation.

00:54:00.330 --> 00:54:02.820
You can have all the
competition in the world.

00:54:02.820 --> 00:54:06.810
It's not going to change the
prevailing wage in a Baumol

00:54:06.810 --> 00:54:09.390
disease industry.

00:54:09.390 --> 00:54:13.680
You are going to have
to pay the Baumol

00:54:13.680 --> 00:54:16.530
premium that Baumol identified.

00:54:16.530 --> 00:54:20.160
What you may escape
is the premium

00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:23.820
on top of Baumol that
Javier identified,

00:54:23.820 --> 00:54:26.010
which is coming out of
the political leverage.

00:54:26.010 --> 00:54:28.220
As opposed to the
workplace leverage

00:54:28.220 --> 00:54:33.800
that unions and contractors
have in the legislature

00:54:33.800 --> 00:54:36.490
on affecting the--

00:54:36.490 --> 00:54:41.420
So you shouldn't,
theoretically, expect no matter

00:54:41.420 --> 00:54:43.730
how skillful you are
with contracting out,

00:54:43.730 --> 00:54:46.220
no matter how much
competition you get,

00:54:46.220 --> 00:54:50.990
you will still need to pay
something like the prevailing

00:54:50.990 --> 00:54:53.030
wage or you won't have workers.

00:54:53.030 --> 00:54:54.887
If you pay too little,
you'll get workers

00:54:54.887 --> 00:54:57.470
with very bad habits, who don't
show up on Monday because they

00:54:57.470 --> 00:54:58.910
went drinking over the weekend.

00:54:58.910 --> 00:55:01.610
And you start providing
a lousy service.

00:55:01.610 --> 00:55:10.130
So you are stuck with the
problem that Baumol identified.

00:55:10.130 --> 00:55:13.220
What you may reduce
is the premium

00:55:13.220 --> 00:55:16.370
on top of that that comes from
the political complication,

00:55:16.370 --> 00:55:20.050
the political power of
labor, and companies

00:55:20.050 --> 00:55:25.370
in the legislative process that
is providing the subsidy, which

00:55:25.370 --> 00:55:27.650
is essential to deal with it.

00:55:27.650 --> 00:55:31.310
The first practical question
for Baumol's disease industry

00:55:31.310 --> 00:55:32.990
is where are you going
to get the money?

00:55:32.990 --> 00:55:34.860
You need the subsidy.

00:55:34.860 --> 00:55:36.380
And then the process
for getting it

00:55:36.380 --> 00:55:37.790
has these other complications.

00:55:37.790 --> 00:55:39.410
Yes?

00:55:39.410 --> 00:55:40.910
AUDIENCE: So basically
you're saying

00:55:40.910 --> 00:55:42.368
it's the government
themselves that

00:55:42.368 --> 00:55:44.840
pay the subsidy to the
contractor to induce them

00:55:44.840 --> 00:55:48.500
to participate in the market?

00:55:48.500 --> 00:55:50.814
Because basically
the private companies

00:55:50.814 --> 00:55:52.230
aren't subject to
Baumol's disease

00:55:52.230 --> 00:55:57.330
because they wouldn't take the
contractor to do the business,

00:55:57.330 --> 00:56:01.080
unless the government
pays them [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:02.520
counteract Baumol's disease.

00:56:02.520 --> 00:56:03.010
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Right.

00:56:03.010 --> 00:56:04.930
So even if there's
lots of competition,

00:56:04.930 --> 00:56:06.880
and there are 10
different companies,

00:56:06.880 --> 00:56:08.410
they're not going
to bid below what

00:56:08.410 --> 00:56:10.730
it's going to cost them
to offer the service.

00:56:10.730 --> 00:56:13.240
They're going to have to
pay the prevailing wage.

00:56:13.240 --> 00:56:16.510
So don't be surprised
over a decade when

00:56:16.510 --> 00:56:17.980
you see that that's
gone up faster

00:56:17.980 --> 00:56:19.510
than the rate of inflation.

00:56:19.510 --> 00:56:23.020
If you should define
success as being,

00:56:23.020 --> 00:56:25.960
if you would
maintain that growth

00:56:25.960 --> 00:56:29.030
at or below the
rate of inflation,

00:56:29.030 --> 00:56:33.030
in the prevailing wage, then
you're doing something right.

00:56:33.030 --> 00:56:36.850
Now, if simultaneously
the region is growing,

00:56:36.850 --> 00:56:38.710
so are these external benefits.

00:56:38.710 --> 00:56:42.220
And you're able to actually
charge more for the service

00:56:42.220 --> 00:56:45.400
as they have been at
transport for London,

00:56:45.400 --> 00:56:48.580
then you may actually
begin to offset

00:56:48.580 --> 00:56:52.480
even that part of the problem
that Baumol identified.

00:56:52.480 --> 00:56:56.050
But the point is
that contracting out

00:56:56.050 --> 00:57:00.170
is an interesting strategy,
but it's not a panacea.

00:57:00.170 --> 00:57:04.570
It's unlikely to get you
below the Baumol threshold,

00:57:04.570 --> 00:57:05.270
so to speak.

00:57:05.270 --> 00:57:07.000
But it may get you--

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:10.180
it may help you reduce this
premium that you'd otherwise

00:57:10.180 --> 00:57:13.000
be condemned to pay.

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:19.890
So this diagram is
just a way of saying

00:57:19.890 --> 00:57:23.100
once you're running a
business subsidized,

00:57:23.100 --> 00:57:26.520
your organization chart
is really complicated.

00:57:26.520 --> 00:57:29.610
I mean in Massachusetts
you've got a governor,

00:57:29.610 --> 00:57:32.160
the Secretary of Transportation
serves at the pleasure

00:57:32.160 --> 00:57:33.660
of the governor.

00:57:33.660 --> 00:57:34.970
There's a board of directors.

00:57:34.970 --> 00:57:36.053
There's a general manager.

00:57:38.680 --> 00:57:42.230
In some, just within
Massachusetts,

00:57:42.230 --> 00:57:45.217
there have been times when
the general managers served

00:57:45.217 --> 00:57:46.550
at the pleasure of the governor.

00:57:46.550 --> 00:57:48.758
There have been other times
when the general managers

00:57:48.758 --> 00:57:52.080
at a contract from the board.

00:57:52.080 --> 00:57:56.030
So if you've got a
situation where there's

00:57:56.030 --> 00:58:00.260
a secretary, a board, and
the general manager, now

00:58:00.260 --> 00:58:00.980
who's the boss?

00:58:00.980 --> 00:58:02.000
Is that the secretary?

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:03.920
Is it the board?

00:58:03.920 --> 00:58:08.030
That general manager then has to
manage this production system.

00:58:08.030 --> 00:58:09.620
Has to worry about customers.

00:58:09.620 --> 00:58:11.630
Has to worry about fares.

00:58:11.630 --> 00:58:13.720
But he's got to deal with labor.

00:58:13.720 --> 00:58:15.800
Needs support for the taxes.

00:58:15.800 --> 00:58:16.870
Who controls that?

00:58:16.870 --> 00:58:19.150
Congress, the legislature?

00:58:19.150 --> 00:58:24.230
Labors got more access
to those sources of power

00:58:24.230 --> 00:58:26.797
than the management
structure does.

00:58:26.797 --> 00:58:29.130
The governor who's supposed
to be on top of all of this,

00:58:29.130 --> 00:58:31.380
he may be from a different
party than the legislature.

00:58:31.380 --> 00:58:34.910
Legislature may not even like
the guy, so he's not much use.

00:58:34.910 --> 00:58:38.270
What's going to get you
votes in the legislature

00:58:38.270 --> 00:58:42.591
for some law that's going to
help you run a better transit

00:58:42.591 --> 00:58:43.090
system?

00:58:43.090 --> 00:58:45.850
It might be capital
to buy new buses.

00:58:45.850 --> 00:58:48.720
Might be just the
operating subsidy.

00:58:48.720 --> 00:58:50.760
Labor's a big piece of this.

00:58:50.760 --> 00:58:55.500
So you've got to recognize
the kind of power

00:58:55.500 --> 00:58:57.840
and influence they're
going to have.

00:58:57.840 --> 00:59:01.620
So let's talk about the
history of the labor movement.

00:59:01.620 --> 00:59:04.290
Talked last time a little
bit about the commons union,

00:59:04.290 --> 00:59:05.310
the eight hour day.

00:59:11.100 --> 00:59:15.290
What's the story with
immigrants and labor?

00:59:15.290 --> 00:59:22.300
We all holding hands,
singing solidarity forever,

00:59:22.300 --> 00:59:27.940
American-born immigrants
all loving each other?

00:59:27.940 --> 00:59:30.732
AUDIENCE: Immigrants always
get the scraps of work.

00:59:30.732 --> 00:59:32.190
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
Yes, immigrants

00:59:32.190 --> 00:59:33.200
are the last ones in.

00:59:33.200 --> 00:59:38.160
So whoever is the earlier group
tends to dominate the jobs.

00:59:38.160 --> 00:59:40.110
Tend to dominate the
management structure.

00:59:40.110 --> 00:59:44.340
Tends to dominate the power
positions within the union.

00:59:44.340 --> 00:59:48.720
So there's not this--

00:59:48.720 --> 00:59:51.600
there's not real solidarity
within the union.

00:59:51.600 --> 00:59:53.970
You get factions
within the union.

00:59:53.970 --> 00:59:59.400
And the newest immigrants
are usually underrepresented,

00:59:59.400 --> 01:00:04.560
sometimes dramatically
so by the union.

01:00:04.560 --> 01:00:09.400
We had a situation at the
T, where through a fluke

01:00:09.400 --> 01:00:12.390
we were able to hire
part-time workers.

01:00:12.390 --> 01:00:16.490
This piece of
legislation went through.

01:00:16.490 --> 01:00:19.700
And the pay scale for the
part-time workers without it

01:00:19.700 --> 01:00:21.590
was outrageously
low, and did not

01:00:21.590 --> 01:00:24.440
include health care benefits.

01:00:24.440 --> 01:00:25.620
Well, I was really offended.

01:00:25.620 --> 01:00:26.870
I said, we're a public agency.

01:00:26.870 --> 01:00:30.740
We're treating these
people horribly.

01:00:30.740 --> 01:00:35.000
And we don't want
them to hate us.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:37.520
I would hate us if I
had to work these hours

01:00:37.520 --> 01:00:41.540
without a decent pay,
without health care benefits.

01:00:41.540 --> 01:00:46.260
Let's at least pay
health care benefits.

01:00:46.260 --> 01:00:48.990
Union says no,
you can't do that.

01:00:48.990 --> 01:00:52.860
You can't confer a benefit
except through the bargaining

01:00:52.860 --> 01:00:54.310
process.

01:00:54.310 --> 01:00:58.200
Oh, well surely you agree
that your dues paying members

01:00:58.200 --> 01:00:59.740
should have health
care benefits.

01:00:59.740 --> 01:01:00.780
Nope, we don't care.

01:01:03.870 --> 01:01:05.079
You're taking their dues.

01:01:05.079 --> 01:01:06.495
You're supposed
to represent them.

01:01:06.495 --> 01:01:06.870
Nope.

01:01:06.870 --> 01:01:08.578
You're going to have
to give us something

01:01:08.578 --> 01:01:11.160
if you want us to allow
you to pay benefits

01:01:11.160 --> 01:01:14.280
to those part-time employees.

01:01:14.280 --> 01:01:16.980
I mean you'd like
to strangle them,

01:01:16.980 --> 01:01:22.347
but there are rules
to bargaining, and so

01:01:22.347 --> 01:01:27.430
[INAUDIBLE] that are
all about leverage,

01:01:27.430 --> 01:01:30.400
and very little
about public policy.

01:01:30.400 --> 01:01:34.710
And your first expectation
about how people will behave

01:01:34.710 --> 01:01:36.860
is very often not the case.

01:01:36.860 --> 01:01:40.390
There are these sort
of perverse incentives.

01:01:40.390 --> 01:01:44.800
And the first preoccupation
on the Union side

01:01:44.800 --> 01:01:47.930
is usually to get re-elected.

01:01:47.930 --> 01:01:49.670
And the more
democratic the union--

01:01:49.670 --> 01:01:51.110
do you think
democratic unions are

01:01:51.110 --> 01:01:54.440
better than autocratic unions?

01:01:54.440 --> 01:01:57.290
How many people vote
for democratic unions?

01:01:57.290 --> 01:01:59.180
AUDIENCE: Can you
explain the difference?

01:01:59.180 --> 01:02:00.680
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
Democratic union

01:02:00.680 --> 01:02:03.800
is one where there are
elections every couple of years.

01:02:03.800 --> 01:02:06.860
And often the
president of the Union

01:02:06.860 --> 01:02:08.690
loses, and a new
president comes in.

01:02:08.690 --> 01:02:12.020
And there's a real give
and take and debate.

01:02:12.020 --> 01:02:15.800
So in the autocratic
union there's

01:02:15.800 --> 01:02:19.910
a family that's been the
president and business

01:02:19.910 --> 01:02:21.990
agent for the past 25 years.

01:02:21.990 --> 01:02:27.350
And when the old man gets
old, his nephew gets the job.

01:02:27.350 --> 01:02:29.970
So you got both kinds
of unions around here.

01:02:29.970 --> 01:02:32.818
Which one do you
think is preferable?

01:02:32.818 --> 01:02:35.108
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] better
for the workers or profit

01:02:35.108 --> 01:02:37.286
[INAUDIBLE]

01:02:37.286 --> 01:02:38.660
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
Well, either.

01:02:38.660 --> 01:02:39.800
Take it separately.

01:02:39.800 --> 01:02:40.939
Better for the workers.

01:02:40.939 --> 01:02:42.980
AUDIENCE: Just because
you're asking the question

01:02:42.980 --> 01:02:44.420
I'm going to go with autocrat.

01:02:44.420 --> 01:02:46.820
I think it's a tie.

01:02:46.820 --> 01:02:50.960
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes,
well the democratic union--

01:02:50.960 --> 01:02:54.200
the union is-- the
union leader is

01:02:54.200 --> 01:02:57.200
so afraid he'll lose
the next election,

01:02:57.200 --> 01:02:59.790
he won't make any decisions.

01:02:59.790 --> 01:03:06.080
So we, at one point,
had hired smart people

01:03:06.080 --> 01:03:08.450
like John Attanucci
to figure out

01:03:08.450 --> 01:03:09.872
better ways of producing stuff.

01:03:09.872 --> 01:03:11.330
And they run these
numbers and say,

01:03:11.330 --> 01:03:17.300
hey, we can structure the
work for the rail side

01:03:17.300 --> 01:03:22.000
into four 10 hour
days, a 40 hour week.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:23.590
People will get long weekends.

01:03:23.590 --> 01:03:25.810
We can make the numbers work.

01:03:25.810 --> 01:03:28.900
It'll save us money,
and the employees

01:03:28.900 --> 01:03:33.299
will make the same money
and have three day weekends.

01:03:33.299 --> 01:03:34.840
And they sort of
test it with people,

01:03:34.840 --> 01:03:38.200
and the workers
really like this idea.

01:03:38.200 --> 01:03:41.390
Union wouldn't accept it,
because they were afraid

01:03:41.390 --> 01:03:43.580
that it would become an issue.

01:03:43.580 --> 01:03:46.280
So you couldn't even
give them something

01:03:46.280 --> 01:03:50.180
that you knew the workers wanted
because they were so weak.

01:03:50.180 --> 01:03:51.740
They were afraid to make a deal.

01:03:51.740 --> 01:03:53.840
You get a more autocratic
union, and there

01:03:53.840 --> 01:03:56.372
are some not so nice
things about the autocrats,

01:03:56.372 --> 01:03:57.830
but they're willing
to make a deal.

01:03:57.830 --> 01:04:00.260
They know they're going
to be president next year.

01:04:00.260 --> 01:04:03.034
They've got enough confidence
they're going to get reelected,

01:04:03.034 --> 01:04:04.950
that they're better able
to step back and say,

01:04:04.950 --> 01:04:07.040
well, what's the long view here.

01:04:07.040 --> 01:04:11.150
And they may be exercising
that power, on a good day,

01:04:11.150 --> 01:04:14.780
they're exercising that power
on behalf of the workers.

01:04:14.780 --> 01:04:19.790
But they're not so
hypersensitive to a faction

01:04:19.790 --> 01:04:23.210
that they're unwilling
to make a deal.

01:04:23.210 --> 01:04:26.030
In the dynamic of
the union, the union

01:04:26.030 --> 01:04:28.340
is just like any
other organization.

01:04:28.340 --> 01:04:31.100
The people who count are
the people who show up.

01:04:31.100 --> 01:04:37.010
So you have a union meeting
once a month, who shows up?

01:04:37.010 --> 01:04:38.680
A small subset of people.

01:04:38.680 --> 01:04:40.520
Everybody else--
Everyone else is

01:04:40.520 --> 01:04:43.079
out bowling or watching
television, or doing

01:04:43.079 --> 01:04:44.120
whatever they like to do.

01:04:44.120 --> 01:04:45.453
They don't go to union meetings.

01:04:45.453 --> 01:04:47.960
So you got to take
care of the ones who

01:04:47.960 --> 01:04:50.900
show up at the meetings, because
that's the attentive public.

01:04:50.900 --> 01:04:53.300
They're the ones that
are paying attention.

01:04:53.300 --> 01:04:58.400
So the dynamic within the union
may appear to be democratic,

01:04:58.400 --> 01:05:02.360
but it's also dominated
by small factions

01:05:02.360 --> 01:05:06.430
whose interests may diverge
from that of the larger group.

01:05:06.430 --> 01:05:10.070
And especially if there has
been a period of ethnic change.

01:05:10.070 --> 01:05:13.550
Typically, the dominant
group in the union

01:05:13.550 --> 01:05:19.070
reflects the ethnic
composition of 25 years ago.

01:05:19.070 --> 01:05:24.861
And the smarter ones realize
that they better pay attention

01:05:24.861 --> 01:05:26.360
to the new workers,
or they're going

01:05:26.360 --> 01:05:29.270
to lose their
positions more quickly.

01:05:29.270 --> 01:05:31.600
But the nastier ones just
say, the hell with it.

01:05:31.600 --> 01:05:33.174
I'm going to take
care of my people,

01:05:33.174 --> 01:05:34.340
and I don't care about them.

01:05:34.340 --> 01:05:39.590
So democracy is a mixed
blessing sometimes.

01:05:39.590 --> 01:05:42.710
But it always makes it
interesting and complicated.

01:05:45.460 --> 01:05:50.570
Go to Item H because we're
running out of time here.

01:05:50.570 --> 01:05:53.755
World War II labor shortages,
wage and price control.

01:05:59.090 --> 01:06:03.500
Do any of you know the
story of the World War II

01:06:03.500 --> 01:06:04.882
wage and price controls?

01:06:04.882 --> 01:06:05.840
What was going on then?

01:06:05.840 --> 01:06:07.850
AUDIENCE: Wages were frozen.

01:06:07.850 --> 01:06:08.810
Yes.

01:06:08.810 --> 01:06:12.350
So consumption of
products was also frozen.

01:06:12.350 --> 01:06:14.660
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes,
because the government was--

01:06:14.660 --> 01:06:16.010
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] war.

01:06:16.010 --> 01:06:18.620
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes, and
the government was afraid of,

01:06:18.620 --> 01:06:21.140
that the shortages would
lead to price spikes,

01:06:21.140 --> 01:06:23.060
and there'd a huge
political backlash.

01:06:23.060 --> 01:06:26.760
So they put in wage
and price controls.

01:06:26.760 --> 01:06:29.150
So the industries that were
producing, particularly

01:06:29.150 --> 01:06:31.310
for the war effort,
because that's

01:06:31.310 --> 01:06:33.560
where the was a lot
of money to be made,

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:35.810
needed to attract workers.

01:06:35.810 --> 01:06:41.219
But they couldn't offer
higher wages under the rules.

01:06:41.219 --> 01:06:43.010
They started offering
health care benefits.

01:06:43.010 --> 01:06:45.800
It was the only way
they could compete.

01:06:45.800 --> 01:06:49.610
At the end of the war, some of
the socialist labor leaders,

01:06:49.610 --> 01:06:52.370
Walter Reuther and
others, looking

01:06:52.370 --> 01:06:55.860
at what was going
on in Europe said,

01:06:55.860 --> 01:06:58.070
well, this is a stupid
way to fund health care.

01:06:58.070 --> 01:06:59.730
Let's have health
care for everybody,

01:06:59.730 --> 01:07:02.610
and let's do it in an
across the board way.

01:07:02.610 --> 01:07:06.970
And the big businesses said
no, we like it this way,

01:07:06.970 --> 01:07:10.410
because this gives us an
advantage that our workers are

01:07:10.410 --> 01:07:12.660
getting health benefits,
and the other aren't.

01:07:12.660 --> 01:07:14.250
And that's to our benefit.

01:07:14.250 --> 01:07:18.870
So these bastards who yap about
out-of-control health care

01:07:18.870 --> 01:07:23.100
costs, the reason we've got
this backward system we've got

01:07:23.100 --> 01:07:26.010
is because of their greed,
and their unwillingness

01:07:26.010 --> 01:07:28.710
in the post-world War II
environment, when you really

01:07:28.710 --> 01:07:31.590
could have gotten a much
broader base Medicare

01:07:31.590 --> 01:07:33.712
for all kind of approach.

01:07:33.712 --> 01:07:34.920
They didn't want it that way.

01:07:34.920 --> 01:07:36.503
Now they complain
that they're paying.

01:07:36.503 --> 01:07:38.160
And I don't blame
them for complaining.

01:07:38.160 --> 01:07:41.040
The system now,
it's kind of weird.

01:07:41.040 --> 01:07:46.680
But it was a product of
the peculiar politics

01:07:46.680 --> 01:07:49.420
of that point in time.

01:07:49.420 --> 01:07:54.230
And you also do
get, theoretically,

01:07:54.230 --> 01:07:59.150
it's possible that
labor unions might

01:07:59.150 --> 01:08:04.640
like the idea that only
union members get health care

01:08:04.640 --> 01:08:05.330
benefits.

01:08:05.330 --> 01:08:08.000
And that they're not conferred
on the whole population,

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:11.270
because it's another
reason to join the union.

01:08:11.270 --> 01:08:14.390
Fortunately the unions
aren't that narrow.

01:08:14.390 --> 01:08:16.970
And they tend to be a
little bit more progressive.

01:08:16.970 --> 01:08:21.380
But they're acting against
their own interests, in a sense.

01:08:21.380 --> 01:08:24.920
It does confer some
advantage on them

01:08:24.920 --> 01:08:28.370
if health care has
to be bargained for.

01:08:28.370 --> 01:08:31.069
It's a reason to join a union,
and be active in the union.

01:08:31.069 --> 01:08:33.319
So you get all these
perverse incentives that

01:08:33.319 --> 01:08:35.810
come out of this kind of stuff.

01:08:35.810 --> 01:08:39.120
We talked about right
to work a little bit.

01:08:39.120 --> 01:08:44.250
So item C, ridership growth
is never instantaneous.

01:08:44.250 --> 01:08:47.235
The point that [INAUDIBLE]
made earlier in the class.

01:08:50.130 --> 01:08:53.439
A lot of important things
take time to achieve.

01:08:53.439 --> 01:08:56.670
You don't instantaneously
get a benefit.

01:08:56.670 --> 01:09:00.750
If you provide more service,
and you guessed right,

01:09:00.750 --> 01:09:03.342
maybe there'll be a
ridership growth in the area

01:09:03.342 --> 01:09:04.800
that you're providing
more service.

01:09:04.800 --> 01:09:07.109
But it doesn't happen
the day you start.

01:09:07.109 --> 01:09:09.010
It's going to take
time to build.

01:09:09.010 --> 01:09:14.490
And that time
period, and the lag

01:09:14.490 --> 01:09:18.120
with which-- even if you get
really well and a lot of riders

01:09:18.120 --> 01:09:21.090
come, and you generate
a lot more revenue,

01:09:21.090 --> 01:09:23.760
that revenue is going to
come later than the cost

01:09:23.760 --> 01:09:25.830
that you have to
expend early on.

01:09:25.830 --> 01:09:33.190
So you get this sort of
swerve in your pattern.

01:09:36.010 --> 01:09:39.300
Now, this is a
couple of years old,

01:09:39.300 --> 01:09:40.960
but unfortunately
it's still true.

01:09:40.960 --> 01:09:42.689
There's this sort
of nasty attitude

01:09:42.689 --> 01:09:45.279
that well, we've got
to grind down costs.

01:09:45.279 --> 01:09:46.529
We've got to grind down costs.

01:09:46.529 --> 01:09:48.970
We've got to grind on costs.

01:09:48.970 --> 01:09:51.550
But the only reason we
have a transit system

01:09:51.550 --> 01:09:54.149
here is it actually happens to
be important to the economy.

01:09:54.149 --> 01:09:55.940
And we're lucky that
the economy's growing.

01:09:55.940 --> 01:09:58.240
We actually need more service.

01:09:58.240 --> 01:10:04.810
So to me, it's more important
to provide more service

01:10:04.810 --> 01:10:07.765
than it is to grind down
the cost of the service.

01:10:11.110 --> 01:10:14.350
If the only thing you're doing
is quote "saving money," then

01:10:14.350 --> 01:10:16.690
shut the system down
and save all the money.

01:10:16.690 --> 01:10:18.640
Presumably, you're
around because you're

01:10:18.640 --> 01:10:20.710
providing something of value.

01:10:20.710 --> 01:10:24.880
And you ought to be providing
higher value, and more of it,

01:10:24.880 --> 01:10:26.614
up to some reasonable limit.

01:10:26.614 --> 01:10:28.030
But certainly I
don't think anyone

01:10:28.030 --> 01:10:30.370
who rides the T
would argue we've

01:10:30.370 --> 01:10:35.260
reached the level where there's
too much service out there.

01:10:35.260 --> 01:10:39.430
We've got a long way to go
in improving service to get

01:10:39.430 --> 01:10:41.170
anywhere near to such a danger.

01:10:43.900 --> 01:10:48.670
This brings me back to this
question of contracting out.

01:10:48.670 --> 01:10:53.050
Because to me, most of the
discussion about contracting

01:10:53.050 --> 01:10:56.460
out, if you're reading the
Boston papers, is about,

01:10:56.460 --> 01:10:59.140
oh we'll contract out
and we'll save money.

01:10:59.140 --> 01:11:01.360
And labor costs too much,
and blah, blah, blah.

01:11:01.360 --> 01:11:04.900
In the first place, you're
not going to save much money.

01:11:04.900 --> 01:11:07.960
The workers-- Paul
Revere, the company

01:11:07.960 --> 01:11:14.230
that runs the blue M2 bus
that you see on Mass Avenue,

01:11:14.230 --> 01:11:16.737
they're also a union operation.

01:11:16.737 --> 01:11:18.070
They've got the Teamsters Union.

01:11:18.070 --> 01:11:19.486
They provide health
care benefits.

01:11:19.486 --> 01:11:21.400
They pay decently.

01:11:21.400 --> 01:11:28.430
It's not about-- a good, private
contracting scheme in my view,

01:11:28.430 --> 01:11:32.110
is not about paying
workers less.

01:11:32.110 --> 01:11:34.360
It's about providing
a better service.

01:11:34.360 --> 01:11:37.890
How many of you use
the number one bus?

01:11:37.890 --> 01:11:41.970
And are any of you able
to use the M2 shuttle?

01:11:41.970 --> 01:11:45.700
OK, which one comes
first usually?

01:11:45.700 --> 01:11:50.590
AUDIENCE: M2, the one
depending on the day.

01:11:50.590 --> 01:11:52.330
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Which one--

01:11:52.330 --> 01:11:55.180
which one are you more
likely to find a seat on?

01:11:55.180 --> 01:11:56.920
AUDIENCE: M2.

01:11:56.920 --> 01:11:58.910
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: The
M2 is a better service.

01:11:58.910 --> 01:12:01.280
That's what you could get.

01:12:01.280 --> 01:12:04.010
That's not because the T
is inherently inferior.

01:12:04.010 --> 01:12:07.010
There is not enough
service on that line.

01:12:07.010 --> 01:12:09.650
But Paul Revere runs
a reasonable service

01:12:09.650 --> 01:12:12.970
because, if they don't, they
won't get chosen next time.

01:12:12.970 --> 01:12:20.060
There is some competition, not
just for cost, but for quality.

01:12:20.060 --> 01:12:22.460
And to me, you want
to be in that area.

01:12:22.460 --> 01:12:28.660
And the other issue is if
you want to increase service,

01:12:28.660 --> 01:12:33.190
and you talk to the
MBTA, you go to a meeting

01:12:33.190 --> 01:12:35.140
and say the service is lousy.

01:12:35.140 --> 01:12:38.170
We want more bus service
on the number one bus.

01:12:38.170 --> 01:12:41.860
And the answer is, fine
what service would you

01:12:41.860 --> 01:12:46.180
suggest we cut so we can reroute
those buses onto the number

01:12:46.180 --> 01:12:47.170
one?

01:12:47.170 --> 01:12:48.920
We'll cut the
baloney, that's crazy.

01:12:48.920 --> 01:12:50.890
Those other routes
need the service too.

01:12:50.890 --> 01:12:52.840
They're in this
sum zero game where

01:12:52.840 --> 01:12:56.500
they refuse to add service
except by taking away.

01:12:56.500 --> 01:12:59.080
Consequently they
never add service.

01:12:59.080 --> 01:13:00.790
And they said, well,
it's a tough world.

01:13:00.790 --> 01:13:02.040
We only get so much equipment.

01:13:02.040 --> 01:13:03.280
We only got so much drivers.

01:13:03.280 --> 01:13:05.860
We only have so many
maintenance facilities,

01:13:05.860 --> 01:13:07.580
land of 1,000 excuses.

01:13:07.580 --> 01:13:09.110
We can't expand.

01:13:09.110 --> 01:13:12.010
You want more service,
contract for it.

01:13:12.010 --> 01:13:13.390
Put some money on the table.

01:13:13.390 --> 01:13:16.360
Have a bid, work and
get some competition

01:13:16.360 --> 01:13:17.945
so it isn't just Paul Revere.

01:13:17.945 --> 01:13:19.570
You'll get more
service a hell of a lot

01:13:19.570 --> 01:13:21.790
faster than you
will ever get it out

01:13:21.790 --> 01:13:23.110
of the public sector machine.

01:13:23.110 --> 01:13:30.580
So I think there's a pro rider
argument for contracting out

01:13:30.580 --> 01:13:33.910
that I believe is quite valid.

01:13:33.910 --> 01:13:35.230
But no one makes that.

01:13:35.230 --> 01:13:41.060
You have this kind of contest
between the anti-cost,

01:13:41.060 --> 01:13:44.360
grind down workers, it's a
victory if we pay people less.

01:13:47.140 --> 01:13:51.940
And the union that says,
do everything in-house.

01:13:51.940 --> 01:13:53.740
Neither of those
parties is really

01:13:53.740 --> 01:13:56.260
speaking on behalf
of the riding public.

01:13:56.260 --> 01:14:00.220
So you want to think
about those aspects.

01:14:00.220 --> 01:14:03.670
Usually people talk about
the union relationship

01:14:03.670 --> 01:14:07.120
as bargaining for--

01:14:07.120 --> 01:14:08.530
union wants higher wages.

01:14:08.530 --> 01:14:13.250
Management wants lower
wages, et cetera, et cetera.

01:14:13.250 --> 01:14:16.380
Bargaining takes
place periodically.

01:14:16.380 --> 01:14:18.210
You might have a
two year contract,

01:14:18.210 --> 01:14:21.680
you might have a
three year contract.

01:14:21.680 --> 01:14:24.710
You set the terms in wages
and working conditions

01:14:24.710 --> 01:14:25.490
for that period.

01:14:25.490 --> 01:14:27.320
Then you bargain again.

01:14:27.320 --> 01:14:29.240
If you can't reach
agreement, there

01:14:29.240 --> 01:14:32.540
are procedures for
binding arbitration.

01:14:32.540 --> 01:14:36.437
Why do we have
binding arbitration?

01:14:36.437 --> 01:14:37.770
Why don't we just have a strike?

01:14:40.380 --> 01:14:41.730
You know?

01:14:41.730 --> 01:14:44.460
AUDIENCE: Why do
we find [INAUDIBLE]

01:14:44.460 --> 01:14:45.460
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes.

01:14:45.460 --> 01:14:48.280
At the MBTA we have
binding arbitration.

01:14:48.280 --> 01:14:51.220
It's not the case in every
transit agency in the country.

01:14:51.220 --> 01:14:53.602
In Philadelphia if they
can't reach agreement,

01:14:53.602 --> 01:14:54.310
there's a strike.

01:14:58.094 --> 01:14:59.746
AUDIENCE: They put
it in state law.

01:14:59.746 --> 01:15:02.204
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes, why
was it put into the state law?

01:15:02.204 --> 01:15:03.580
AUDIENCE: To avoid strike.

01:15:03.580 --> 01:15:04.580
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes.

01:15:04.580 --> 01:15:06.770
So in Massachusetts the
thing was, wait a minute,

01:15:06.770 --> 01:15:11.450
strikes are really
painful for everybody.

01:15:11.450 --> 01:15:14.660
Let's just have a
bureaucratic process

01:15:14.660 --> 01:15:18.350
to settle disputes
that can't be resolved,

01:15:18.350 --> 01:15:19.650
but let's not have a strike.

01:15:19.650 --> 01:15:21.650
Too many people are hurt
when you have a strike.

01:15:21.650 --> 01:15:24.860
The workers-- workers lose
their health care benefits.

01:15:24.860 --> 01:15:28.010
I mean, your kid's
got a kidney problem,

01:15:28.010 --> 01:15:30.710
and you have no health
care, that's a problem.

01:15:30.710 --> 01:15:33.060
So it's a problem for the
worker to be on strike.

01:15:33.060 --> 01:15:34.410
It's not easy.

01:15:34.410 --> 01:15:36.950
It's a problem for the
public, there's no service.

01:15:36.950 --> 01:15:40.920
So binding arbitration
I think is a good idea.

01:15:40.920 --> 01:15:43.460
There are those who argue the
Philadelphia system is better.

01:15:43.460 --> 01:15:44.330
I think it's wacky.

01:15:44.330 --> 01:15:48.010
They shut down the city
every periodically.

01:15:48.010 --> 01:15:49.760
AUDIENCE: They lose
their health insurance

01:15:49.760 --> 01:15:50.719
when they go on strike?

01:15:50.719 --> 01:15:53.009
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Yes, if
you're not employed anymore

01:15:53.009 --> 01:15:54.110
you lose the benefit.

01:15:54.110 --> 01:15:55.568
AUDIENCE: But when
you're on strike

01:15:55.568 --> 01:15:57.240
aren't you still employed?

01:15:57.240 --> 01:16:00.210
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: Not
if the contracts run out.

01:16:00.210 --> 01:16:04.500
I mean it's like,
it's a bizarre world.

01:16:04.500 --> 01:16:07.050
AUDIENCE: But in most
[INAUDIBLE] is that going to be

01:16:07.050 --> 01:16:08.480
the issue, because
if they have--

01:16:08.480 --> 01:16:10.340
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: No.

01:16:10.340 --> 01:16:13.140
Yes, in other places you would
have a more civilized way

01:16:13.140 --> 01:16:15.970
of dealing with it, because you
didn't have this odd World War

01:16:15.970 --> 01:16:16.470
II.

01:16:16.470 --> 01:16:16.770
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:16:16.770 --> 01:16:19.160
AUDIENCE: The English have
way more strikes than we do.

01:16:19.160 --> 01:16:20.987
Maybe that's because they're
not [INAUDIBLE] health

01:16:20.987 --> 01:16:21.960
care when they go on strike.

01:16:21.960 --> 01:16:23.610
FREDERICK SALVUCCI:
That could be true.

01:16:23.610 --> 01:16:25.790
But they also--

01:16:25.790 --> 01:16:28.560
I don't know if those are legal
strikes or illegal strikes.

01:16:28.560 --> 01:16:31.470
Because sometimes
in Massachusetts

01:16:31.470 --> 01:16:36.350
even though we've got
binding arbitration,

01:16:36.350 --> 01:16:38.740
and it's against
the law to strike,

01:16:38.740 --> 01:16:40.860
occasionally they'll walk out.

01:16:40.860 --> 01:16:43.730
And it's very dramatic.

01:16:43.730 --> 01:16:45.270
You put the labor
leaders in jail,

01:16:45.270 --> 01:16:47.900
and that gets them
more votes next time,

01:16:47.900 --> 01:16:50.500
because it shows how committed
they were to the cause.

01:16:50.500 --> 01:16:52.150
A lot of theater involved

01:16:52.150 --> 01:16:59.580
But the only point is the
drama is around the bargaining.

01:16:59.580 --> 01:17:05.140
And potential strike, wildcat
strike, binding arbitration.

01:17:05.140 --> 01:17:08.010
And it's about how much
money in the envelope.

01:17:08.010 --> 01:17:13.320
But at least as important as
what's bargained explicitly,

01:17:13.320 --> 01:17:16.470
is the day to day relationship
between management and labor

01:17:16.470 --> 01:17:20.607
between the bargaining,
because you've got a job to do.

01:17:20.607 --> 01:17:21.690
You've got to run service.

01:17:21.690 --> 01:17:24.220
And there are
these arcane rules.

01:17:24.220 --> 01:17:27.540
And the rules are so arcane that
if you comply with every rule,

01:17:27.540 --> 01:17:29.520
you can't run the service.

01:17:29.520 --> 01:17:32.100
Oh I'm not going to drive the
bus because the windshield

01:17:32.100 --> 01:17:35.560
wiper is broken, and the
rulebook says I can't drive it.

01:17:35.560 --> 01:17:36.420
But it's sunny out.

01:17:36.420 --> 01:17:37.260
It's not raining.

01:17:37.260 --> 01:17:38.219
We'll fix it tonight.

01:17:38.219 --> 01:17:39.760
Nope, I'm not going
to drive the bus.

01:17:39.760 --> 01:17:41.440
It's not in perfect condition.

01:17:41.440 --> 01:17:46.530
So there's always an
informal relationship

01:17:46.530 --> 01:17:49.140
between the employer
and the employee,

01:17:49.140 --> 01:17:52.920
or the management
and the employee.

01:17:52.920 --> 01:17:55.170
And that day to
day relationship is

01:17:55.170 --> 01:17:59.730
very critical to the quality
of service you can provide.

01:17:59.730 --> 01:18:04.560
And the papers never
talk about that aspect

01:18:04.560 --> 01:18:06.240
of the Labor-Management
relationship.

01:18:06.240 --> 01:18:08.070
It's almost always
about the bargaining,

01:18:08.070 --> 01:18:10.444
and how much is in the paycheck,
and what the health care

01:18:10.444 --> 01:18:11.880
benefits are.

01:18:11.880 --> 01:18:18.120
So you really need to think
about the quote unquote

01:18:18.120 --> 01:18:22.140
"culture of the place," and what
it's like to actually provide

01:18:22.140 --> 01:18:24.520
service in a union environment.

01:18:24.520 --> 01:18:27.030
And if you didn't
have a union, you'd

01:18:27.030 --> 01:18:29.220
still have to solve the
problem of how to get--

01:18:29.220 --> 01:18:30.750
how to motivate your workers.

01:18:30.750 --> 01:18:35.790
So it's not-- the union is just
giving you an articulated forum

01:18:35.790 --> 01:18:38.250
to deal with this issue,
which can actually

01:18:38.250 --> 01:18:39.799
be kind of convenient.

01:18:39.799 --> 01:18:41.340
If you don't have
a union, you almost

01:18:41.340 --> 01:18:44.880
need to invent one because you
need some basis to communicate

01:18:44.880 --> 01:18:46.680
with your workers
about, OK, how we're

01:18:46.680 --> 01:18:48.240
going to get this thing done.

01:18:48.240 --> 01:18:55.470
So if you shift your focus from
the paycheck bargaining aspect

01:18:55.470 --> 01:18:59.340
to the management of the
production of the work,

01:18:59.340 --> 01:19:02.725
I think you'll be looking at
the more important problem.

01:19:06.180 --> 01:19:08.440
And I'm out of time
in two minutes.

01:19:08.440 --> 01:19:12.510
So let's see if there's
anything else in here.

01:19:12.510 --> 01:19:15.980
Here, how many of
you have seen this?

01:19:15.980 --> 01:19:18.659
OK so what is it?

01:19:18.659 --> 01:19:20.700
AUDIENCE: They've been
trying to do a few things.

01:19:20.700 --> 01:19:24.560
Trying to get a increase state
income tax by a little bit,

01:19:24.560 --> 01:19:26.275
particularly on the rich.

01:19:26.275 --> 01:19:30.390
And they're trying to
get some more money out

01:19:30.390 --> 01:19:33.882
than what the state provides in
transit, education, and health

01:19:33.882 --> 01:19:34.854
care.

01:19:34.854 --> 01:19:37.290
Or in this case, in transit.

01:19:37.290 --> 01:19:40.080
FREDERICK SALVUCCI: And so
they're putting a lot of energy

01:19:40.080 --> 01:19:41.070
into this.

01:19:41.070 --> 01:19:44.370
And it's a direct--

01:19:44.370 --> 01:19:48.840
the union has gained, in
my view, a lot of leverage.

01:19:48.840 --> 01:19:54.420
Because the management at the
MBTA has been so into we're

01:19:54.420 --> 01:19:57.040
going to privatize
this to save money.

01:19:57.040 --> 01:19:59.340
We can do it cheaper
by contracting it out.

01:19:59.340 --> 01:20:01.950
They never talk about
we can improve service

01:20:01.950 --> 01:20:04.050
by contracting it out.

01:20:04.050 --> 01:20:06.840
So they've totally,
in my view, blown it

01:20:06.840 --> 01:20:10.410
because all they're doing is
saying we can do it cheaper

01:20:10.410 --> 01:20:12.300
if we contract out.

01:20:12.300 --> 01:20:15.090
And they've left
the playing field

01:20:15.090 --> 01:20:19.860
open to labor to pose as
the champion of the riders.

01:20:19.860 --> 01:20:22.800
And say, oh we are
friendly transit providers.

01:20:22.800 --> 01:20:26.100
Give us more money and you
can have better service.

01:20:26.100 --> 01:20:30.690
Never dealing with the fact that
the service production at the T

01:20:30.690 --> 01:20:32.400
is pretty bad.

01:20:32.400 --> 01:20:38.830
And the Paul Revere, private
companies, do a better job.

01:20:38.830 --> 01:20:40.980
They are closer to that
efficiency frontier

01:20:40.980 --> 01:20:43.250
that [INAUDIBLE]
was talking about

01:20:43.250 --> 01:20:49.050
of getting as much
quality service as you can

01:20:49.050 --> 01:20:51.660
out of a given resource base.

01:20:51.660 --> 01:20:55.530
It's always possible to
get less than you paid for.

01:20:55.530 --> 01:20:58.140
It's rare that you can get
more than you paid for.

01:20:58.140 --> 01:21:01.900
That discussion never
happens that there's

01:21:01.900 --> 01:21:03.400
a reason for contracting out.

01:21:03.400 --> 01:21:06.920
Because we can grow faster,
we can provide better service.

01:21:06.920 --> 01:21:08.890
So the playing
field has been left

01:21:08.890 --> 01:21:12.160
totally open to labor
who says management

01:21:12.160 --> 01:21:13.340
doesn't care about you.

01:21:13.340 --> 01:21:15.550
They don't care how
crowded your bus is.

01:21:15.550 --> 01:21:18.760
They don't care how
lousy the service is.

01:21:18.760 --> 01:21:20.620
They're just into
being mean to labor.

01:21:20.620 --> 01:21:23.052
I mean that's basically--

01:21:23.052 --> 01:21:24.510
I think it's a
really dumb strategy

01:21:24.510 --> 01:21:27.180
by the current
management at the T.

01:21:27.180 --> 01:21:28.890
That's a very
objective statement.

01:21:28.890 --> 01:21:34.200
And it's a minute late so, sorry
to go on too long and thanks

01:21:34.200 --> 01:21:36.350
for being here.

